ions of the Caribbean offers a comprehensive introduction to the syncretic religions that have developed in the region. From Vodou, Santería, Regla de Palo, the Abakuá Secret Society, and Obeah to Quimbois and Espiritismo, the volume traces the historical–cultural origins of the major Creole religions, as well as the newer traditions such as Pocomania and Rastafarianism. This second edition updates the scholarship on the religions themselves and also expands the regional considerations of the Diaspora to the U. S. Latino community who are influenced by Creole spiritual practices. Fernández Olmos and Paravisini–Gebert also take into account the increased significance of material culture—art, music, literature—and healing practices influenced by Creole religions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfro-Caribbean cults. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aMurphy, Joseph M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlmos, Margarite Fernández, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814728253.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814728253423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814728253/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles